<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin on Current Inflation Rate, IMF Credits </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin on Current Inflation Rate, IMF Credits </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004192594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1536 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004192594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 20 TASS -- The current rate of 
inflation in Russia at about 8-10 per cent a month opens up 
prospects for credits from the International Monetary Fund, 
Russian President Boris Yeltsin said. Speaking at a meeting with 
the heads of regional administrations in Moscow on Wednesday, 
Yeltsin said that "in April the IMF will allocate Russia 1.5 
billion dollars" if the current level of inflation is 
maintained. If the economic situation improves, Russia may 
count on another 5-7 billion U.S. dollars in the future, he 
added. 
  The president stressed that "the current level of inflation 
in Russia is the lowest in the CIS." It almost meets the target 
figures, although May and June will be difficult, he said. 
Yeltsin stressed that the government is now working on a draft 
budget for 1995 and will submit it to the State Duma, the lower 
house of the Russian Parliament, in September 1994. 

</TEXT>

