<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev Deems NATO Air Strikes `Extremely Dangerous' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grachev Deems NATO Air Strikes `Extremely Dangerous' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004163794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1515 
GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2004163794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Andrey Parlariya and Sergey </F>
Ostanin] 
  [Text] Moscow, 20 Apr -- Army General Pavel Grachev, the 
Russian defense minister, considers that the Bosnian conflict 
can only be resolved by political means. "We reject the use of 
air strikes by UN-operated aircraft, regarding it as extremely 
dangerous," the Russian minister stressed today after signing a 
Russian-Turkish agreement on cooperation in the 
military-technical sphere. He feels that this path will not 
yield any positive results whatsoever. On the contrary, Pavel 
Grachev pointed out, these "often inaccurate strikes humiliate 
the military." 
  He said that the Russian Defense Ministry does not have a 
clear view of the situation around the Bosnian town of Gorazde. 
"We do not believe in whitewashing the Bosnian Serbs. Both 
warring parties are to blame in this situation," Pavel Grachev 
noted. The minister disclosed that on Sunday he had spoken to 
General Mladic, the commander of the Serb Army in Bosnia, and 
had asked him not to attack Gorazde. As a result, the defense 
minister added, the Serbs held their fire for two days, but the 
immediate response of the other side was to go on the offensive. 
  Replying to a question on the possibilities of sending 
additional Russian peacekeeping forces to the former Yugoslavia, 
Pavel Grachev stressed that 200-300 men would not improve the 
situation. In his opinion, in order to solve the Bosnian 
problem by military means it would be necessary to enlist 
60-70,000 servicemen of the UN peacekeeping forces. "But this 
is unrealistic," he noted. "This would mean the beginning of 
large-scale combat operations, war." 
  In Pavel Grachev's opinion, the Russian president's 
initiative, which was expressed on 19 April during his telephone 
conversation with German Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl, is 
worthy of attention. 
  It essentially means that the presidents of Russia and the 
United States, the leaders of the countries of the European 
Community, and the political and military leaders of the former 
Yugoslavia should meet in any European country to discuss the 
prospects for a way out of the crisis. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

