<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Council Discusses Caucasus, Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Security Council Discusses Caucasus, Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2004135694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1333 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2004135694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow April 20 TASS -- The Russian Security Council 
discussed on Wednesday Russia's policy in the Caucasus and the 
implementation of previous decisions calling for support for 
Russian Cossacks, the presidential press service said. 
  Participants in the meeting which was chaired by President 
Boris Yeltsin stressed that Russia's policy in the Caucasus 
should aim at expanding mutually beneficial cooperation with all 
countries of the region, promoting their social and economic 
development, reaching civic accord and restoring stability in 
the region. 
  On the question of state support for Cossacks, the council 
called for working out as soon as possible a federal programme 
for their support. At present, the implementation of decisions 
in this sphere is being hindered by the passivity of federal and 
local bodies of power, lack of coordination and ineffective 
legislation. 
  Yeltsin urged the government, concerned ministries and 
departments to take practical measures to work out and realise 
Russia's policy in the Caucasus and provide state support for 
Russian Cossacks. 
  The press service said that the council also discussed the 
situation in Bosnia and Gorazde. Its members expressed the hope 
that there is still a possibility of resolving the crisis by 
peaceful means. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

