<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rybkin `Not Disappointed' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rybkin `Not Disappointed' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104190694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1608 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104190694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The speaker of the Russian State Duma Ivan Rybkin 
stated that he not disappointed with the discussion of a draft 
treaty on civil accord in the lower chamber of parliament on 
Thursday. Speaking to journalists, he said that speeches by 
deputies were "adequate considering what is happening in the 
country." 
  Rybkin considers that it is far from certain that political 
parties at their conferences, plenums and congresses scheduled 
for this weekend will support positions of their parliamentary 
factions which spoke against signing a civil accord agreement. 
  "Having been to the most remote regions of the country, 
where 
electricity appeared only in the `70s, I get convinced that 
nobody wants conflict, people are seeking accord," the speaker 
pointed out. 
  Rybkin said that during his meeting with the president 
scheduled for April 22 at 15:00 he intends to discuss with Boris 
Yeltsin a further course of debates over the draft agreement. 
  "This is very difficult issue. We should sew with a thin 
needle, and not to take a pitchfork and thrust it in deputies' 
sides," the speaker of the State Duma noted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

