<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-078 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Filatov: Two Options for Dealing with Chechnya </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Filatov: Two Options for Dealing with Chechnya </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104163894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1441 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 21 TASS -- Officials of the Russian 
Presidential Staff and Government are expected to meet in May 
for a series of consultations with various structures of the 
Chechen Republic to prepare talks between the Russian and 
Chechen leaderships, Chief of the Presidential Staff Sergey 
Filatov told TASS on Thursday. 
  He believes that "the public feelings in Chechnya, 
especially 
among the opposition to current President Dzhokhar Dudayev, are 
increasingly proving to the republic's aspiration for closer 
ties with Russia". 
  In contrast to Russian Minister for Nationalities and 
Regional Policy Sergey Shakhray, Filatov does not link the 
proposed talks to early elections in Chechnya. However, he 
still presses the republic for recognizing its status as a 
subject of the Federation and for concluding a bilateral 
agreement similar to that between Russia and Tatarstan. 
Chechnya has not yet clarified its stand on these two issues 
Russia lays down as the necessary condition for talks to get 
under way, the chief of the presidential staff noted. According 
to him, the Chechen side submitted its own draft of a bilateral 
agreement with Russia "which is on the whole quite acceptable 
for consideration in the course of talks", but remained rather 
inarticulate as concerns its status within the Russian 
Federation. 
  Filatov said Russia had a "tough" and a "soft" options in 
settling its differences with Chechnya. The "tough" one 
provides, in particular, for shifting the Russian railway from 
Chechen territory, since crime and plundering on the railway 
exceed all bounds. "but before resorting to tough measures, we 
should try soft ones", he pointed out. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

