<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   N. Ossetian President Speaks Prior to Moscow Trip </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    N. Ossetian President Speaks Prior to Moscow Trip </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104183894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1058 
GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2104183894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Shanayev] </F>
  [Text] Vladikavkaz, 21 Apr -- The upcoming parliamentary 
hearings in the Federation Council and the meeting of the 
Russian Security Council, both of which will discuss the 
situation in the conflict zone, are yet another attempt at 
achieving a peaceful settlement of relations between North 
Ossetia and Ingushetia, Akhsarbek Galazov, president of the 
Republic of North Ossetia, said today in an interview with the 
ITAR-TASS correspondent before leaving by air for Moscow. 
  Akhsarbek Galazov said that North Ossetia is extremely 
interested in establishing normal relations with all its 
neighbors in the North Caucasus region and Transcaucasia. But 
the multinational people of the republic will not accept 
strong-arm methods to resolve these questions. Nor should one 
force the process involving the return of refugees to villages 
in Prigorodnyy Rayon. This complicated problem must be resolved 
by conciliation commissions on the basis of the Kislovodsk 
Agreements. 
  Speaking of the upcoming signing of the agreement on 
achieving civic accord in Russia, the republic's president 
stressed that North Ossetia supports the ideas of this document 
that are aimed at consolidating all the healthy forces in 
society. 
  However, Akhsarbek Galazov noted that "the sides are 
appealing to national movements and parties to declare a 
moratorium on putting forward demands for changes to be made to 
borders and existing administrative divisions." It is necessary 
to take off the agenda the issue of redrawing borders in the 
region. Galazov said that this could lead to a new tragedy not 
only in the North Caucasus, but also in the south of Russia. 

</TEXT>

