<H3> <TI>   Omsk Rocket Builders Licensed To Launch Satellites </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Omsk Rocket Builders Licensed To Launch Satellites </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2204092394 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 20 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PM2204092394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Sergey Suslikov report: "Rocket Seeks Customer"] </F>
  [Text] Omsk -- The "Polet" Aerospace Association, which in 
the recent past manufactured the launch rockets for the "Buran" 
shuttle in Omsk, has obtained a license from the Russian agency 
granting it the right to launch Russian and foreign satellites. 
  "Polet" relies mainly on the "Cosmos" rocket, which is 
capable of lifting large numbers of satellites into orbit for a 
variety of purposes. Evidence from independent European experts 
testifies to the rocket's high class: Only 19 failures in 700 
launches is one of the world's best records. 
  The Russian rocket has a further advantage -- it is cheaper 
than foreign counterparts. All the same, it will not be easy to 
find buyers. The West dictates its own policy in the space 
commercial services market. 

</TEXT>

