<H3> <TI>   Bashkortostan President on Civic Peace Document </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bashkortostan President on Civic Peace Document </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104131694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1127 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104131694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Bashkortostan's President Murtaza Rakhimov believes 
that adoption of the agreement on civic peace and accord in 
Russia proposed by Boris Yeltsin can negatively affect the 
political and social-economic situation in the country. 
  Addressing the Wednesday sitting of the republic's 
Presidential Council, he underlined that introduction of a 
moratorium on acts of a political manner, proposed by the 
agreement, again postponed signing of the bilateral agreement 
between Russia and Bashkortostan for an indefinite time, 
Rakhimov noted that this is being done "at that very moment when 
all issues on this bilateral agreement have been coordinated in 
the course of years of difficult negotiations." 
  Members of the council called on the head of the republic 
not 
to sign this document because it is "a chauvinist document 
infringing upon the rights of the constituent members." 
According to the council, in general the agreement reminds of a 
directive from Moscow sent to the regions without minding the 
interests of the republics within the Russian Federation. 

</TEXT>

