<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lack of Orders Could Leave Space Center `Museum' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lack of Orders Could Leave Space Center `Museum' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2204085194 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1600 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PM2204085194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast: Video report by from St. </F>
Petersburg by M. Velikoselskiy and Ye. Alekseyev, identified by 
caption] 
  [Text] Not many visitors to this museum in St. Petersburg 
have been able to see the entire exhibition. Despite the fact 
that only specialists are admitted to the exhibition halls of 
the Russian Scientific Center of Applied Chemistry, it takes a 
special permit for some doors to be opened. Old women living 
nearby claim that the atom bomb itself was built here. 
  In actual fact the State Institute of Applied Chemistry was 
and is working on other problems, also mainly of a defense 
nature. Engine fuel for space rockets from Gagarin's Vostok to 
the Buran has been developed here. 
  However, in recent years the share of orders from the 
military-industrial complex has totaled less than half of the 
Institute's orders. Now there is not enough money to implement 
ideas, equipment is not being updated, and specialists are 
leaving. Unless the situation improves, this unique scientific 
center will become a subsidiary of its own museum, and no new 
generation of would-be Russian space travelers is likely to 
blast off to remote galaxies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

