<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Regional Television, Radio To Lose Federal Subsidies </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Regional Television, Radio To Lose Federal Subsidies </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2104131094 Moscow Russian Television and Dubl Networks in 
Russian 0600 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2104131094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television and Dubl Networks </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Dalniy Vostok" program] </F>
  [Text] Yet another attempt is being made to reform state 
television and radio broadcasting. It is envisaged to end 
federal financing of 89 regional Russian television and radio 
companies; if local budgets are unable to support them, they 
will be auctioned off and privatized. This is a tempting 
business, and according to the plan's authors it will be of 
value to Russia. Of course, not a single reform in our country 
in the post-Soviet period has hit its mark, and has usually hit 
another target--the one it was meant to defend. Previously, 
innovators had little chance of participating in these attempts 
at reform, but now more successful people have become involved 
in this matter. Possibly they will be the first in Russia to 
promptly manage to do two things at once: break up the old and 
build the new. 

</TEXT>

