Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Negotiations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Negotiations </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Says No `Serious Disagreements' </H4>

<F P=102> LD2104193194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1817 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104193194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian Defense Minister Vitaliy Radetskyy has 
described the atmosphere at current Ukrainian-Russian talks on 
the future of the Black Sea Fleet as "good." 
  He told a news conference in the Crimean city of Sevastopol 
on Thursday [21 April] that there had been no serious 
disagreements during the negotiations. "There was some 
friction, but Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev put 
everything in order," he said. 
  Radetskyy said each side had made its own inventory of the 
fleet, which the two countries plan to divide between them. The 
inventories listed different numbers of vessels, but, if the 
difference was ironed out by Friday, a joint inventory would be 
unnecessary, he said. 
  Radetskyy said Ukraine had proposed that Russia base its 
portion of the fleet at Donuzlav, 100 km (62.5 miles) west of 
Sevastopol. 
  "The delegations had different viewpoints on that. Experts 
are now working on it. We are looking for points of contact and 
will cut that Gordian knot," he said. 
  Asked to comment on Russia's demand to base its part of the 
fleet at Sevastopol, Radetskyy said, "They cannot make any 
demands because they are on Ukrainian territory. The land, 
water and infrastructure belong to Ukraine. They can only make 
proposals, not dictate their terms." "The infrastructure is ours 
and can only be leased to Russia," he emphasized. 
  He said the two sides were looking for a solution but 
"nobody 
has yet taken any concrete decision about that or made any 
promises." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

