<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Negotiations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Negotiations </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Further Details on Talks </H4>

<F P=102> LD2104103894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1001 
GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2104103894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS special correspondent Mikhail Shevtsov] </F>
  [Text] Sevastopol, 21 Apr -- Talks began in Sevastopol this 
afternoon between the Russian and Ukrainian defense ministers, 
Pavel Grachev and Vitaliy Radetskyy. They are meeting to agree 
questions connected with the implementation of the agreement on 
the Black Sea Fleet, signed in Moscow on 15 April by Boris 
Yeltsin and Leonid Kravchuk. Before the talks started, the two 
defense ministers held a private conversation. 
  During the morning, Pavel Grachev met with Black Sea 
sailors. 
He said "the Black Sea fleet was, is, and will remain our 
national pride and glory and it must be retained for Russia," 
stressing that he will do his utmost to ensure that "Sevastopol 
becomes Russia's main base on the Black Sea." Pavel Grachev 
thinks the fleet's problems must be resolved in the interests of 
Russia, Ukraine, and Crimea. "If we manage to agree to leave 85 
percent of the Black Sea Fleet to Russia, it can be regarded as 
a sensible compromise in the talks," the Russian defense 
minister stressed. 
  Crimean President Yuriy Meshkov also thinks the Black Sea 
Fleet ought to be Russian. On the eve of the talks in 
Sevastopol, in which he is not taking part, he told journalists 
he regarded the siting of the Ukrainian Navy headquarters on the 
territory of the peninsula as inadmissible and that he intends 
to ensure that the highest authorities in the Crimea give their 
consent for any redeployment of military formations. 
  The Russian side is also represented at the talks in 
Sevastopol by presidential envoy Yuriy Dubynin and Navy 
Commander in Chief Feliks Gromov. 

</TEXT>

