<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Negotiations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Negotiations </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Official Refutes Baltin Statement </H4>

<F P=102> LD2104180094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1409 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104180094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A high-ranking official in the Ukrainian president's 
administration reported in his interview with the agency 
INTERFAX-Ukraine that the statement by Black Sea Fleet Commander 
Vice Admiral Eduard Baltin saying that as many as 35 percent of 
the Fleet's ships had been already transferred to Ukraine is 
false. In his words, "these ships are being build at the 
Ukrainian shipyards and have nothing in common with the Black 
Sea Fleet." 
  In his interview with INTERFAX on Wednesday Vice Admiral 
Baltin declared that a total of 35 percent of the Fleet had been 
already transferred to Ukraine and "the remained 65 percent are 
to be divided." 
  The official in the presidential administration declared 
that 
"in accordance with the agreements reached in Yalta, Zavidovo, 
Massandra, and Moscow, the Black Sea Fleet ships and crafts will 
be divided on a 50-50 basis." About 20 percent of ships and 
crafts needed for Ukraine's defense will be assigned to it, he 
said. "The remaining 30 percent can be sold to any other 
country, including Russia," he pointed out. 

</TEXT>

