<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Negotiations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Negotiations </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Talks End in `Disarray' </H4>

<F P=102> LD2104165494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1642 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104165494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Shevtsov] </F>
  [Text] Sevastopol 21 April TASS -- The Russian-Ukrainian 
talks on the Black Sea Fleet ended in disarray in Sevastopol on 
Thursday [21 April] after the sides failed to iron out their 
disagreements. 
  The Russian delegation insists that the Russian Black Sea 
Fleet and the Ukrainian Navy should be located in different 
places. The Ukrainian side, however, believes that both can 
stay in Sevastopol, but in different harbours. 
  Russian Defence Minister Pavel Grachev who headed the 
Russian 
delegation to the talks told journalists that at the first 
plenary meeting the sides outlined their positions on the 
matter. Experts were due to resume discussions later in the 
day. The talks will continue on Friday on an enlarged basis. 
  Black Sea Fleet spokesman Andrey Grachev said the Ukrainian 
side is playing a "Massandra scenario" at the talks. Under the 
agreement signed by Russian President Boris Yeltsin and 
Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk in Massandra, the Crimea, in 
1993, Ukraine pledged to sell its part of the fleet to Russia in 
exchange for writing off its debt for Russian energy supplies. 
However, the deal was strongly opposed by the Ukrainian 
military. 
  Ukrainian Defence Minister Vitaliy Radetskyy's refusal to 
allow Crimean President Yuriy Meshkov and Sevastopol city 
council chairman Viktor Semenyov to join in the talks added to 
the tension. 
  Articles five and six of the law on the delineation of 
powers 
between Ukraine and the Crimea allow Crimean leaders to have 
their say in issues connected with the location of troops and 
establishment of new military units in the republic, the 
spokesman said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

