<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karasin on Possible Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karasin on Possible Withdrawal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204110994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1019 
GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2204110994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 22 Apr -- In connection with the reports by 
a number of agencies about the possible withdrawal of Russia's 
peacekeeping battalion in Bosnia-Herzegovina, Grigoriy Karasin, 
director of the Press and Information Department at the Russian 
Foreign Ministry, today said the following to an ITAR-TASS 
diplomatic correspondent: 
  "In the event of an escalation of tension in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina which poses a threat to UNPROFOR [UN 
Protection Force] troops, be it as a result of mass air strikes 
by NATO, or of military activities of the sides directly 
involved in the conflict, then the question could arise of 
whether it is expedient to keep peacekeeping forces in Bosnia. 
The UN secretary general's special envoy, Y. Akashi, also said 
this recently. A whole number of states with peacekeeping 
forces in the zone of conflict have said several times that if a 
real threat to peacekeepers develops, the question may arise of 
withdrawing military contingents. It goes without saying that, 
in this event, the Russian side would not sit with its arms 
folded either." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

