<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Holds Out Hopes for Peace </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Holds Out Hopes for Peace </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104155794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1517 
GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2104155794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 21 Apr -- Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev today expressed the hope that neither the petty 
provocations of the Moslems, the criminal artillery shelling of 
civilian targets in Gorazde, nor the threat of the unleashing of 
an air war in Bosnia will wreck the talks in Belgrade planned 
for 22 April between the UN special envoy Yasushi Akashi and the 
Serb leaders Slobodan Milosevic and Radovan Karadzic. 
  Russia, he noted in a conversation with an ITAR-TASS 
correspondent, has done a great deal and is prepared to continue 
its efforts to establish a lasting interaction between the 
Serbian side and the UN in the hope of settling the situation 
around Gorazde and strengthening the safety zones. It is 
important to move without delay toward a comprehensive reduction 
in all hostilities in Bosnia-Herzegovina, a draft of which has 
already been prepared through the joint efforts of Vitaliy 
Churkin and Charles Redman, the co-chairmen of Russia and the 
United States. 
  I hope, the minister stressed, that the Serbian President S. 
Milosevic will this time be successful in putting into practice 
the policy that was agreed upon during the course of our 
conversation with him during the night of 16-17 April, because 
it is precisely this which meets the interests of the Serbs and 
their traditional relations with Russia. 

</TEXT>

