<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia To Continue Peace Efforts in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia To Continue Peace Efforts in Bosnia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104173194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1440 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature:reports by </F>
diplomatic correspondents Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy Trubetskoy, and 
others] 
  [Text] Russia still possesses the means to exercise 
influence in the former Yugoslavia and will go on trying to make 
the Serbs stop fire, said the Russian president's official 
spokesman. 
  Vyacheslav Kostikov told a news briefing in Moscow on 
Thursday that President Boris Yeltsin insisted that 
highest-level consultations on the Yugoslav issue between 
Russia, the United States, the European Union and the United 
Nations take no more than one month, developments in the 
embattled Balkan country being too fast. 
  Kostikov denied media reports that the latest events in 
Bosnia's Gorazde area had made Russia change its position. 
Moscow still wants a nonviolent settlement, he said. 
  Russia is taking no sides in the conflict, the spokesman 
said. Yeltsin thinks not all nonviolent means have as yet been 
tried, Kostikov said. He said he had had a meeting with Yeltsin 
before the briefing, at which the president repeated his 
objection to air strikes against Bosnian Serb forces. 
  Kostikov denied that a rift had appeared between Russia and 
America. "There are undoubtedly natural contradictions between 
states in their national interests, in economics and politics, 
but Boris Yeltsin believes the main principle underlying the 
policies of the two countries, namely their intention to develop 
cooperation and strengthen the path of democratic development 
has not been changed," he said. 
  He quoted Yeltsin as saying that attempts to "drive a wedge 
between Russia and the United States and between him and 
President Bill Clinton are doomed to failure." 

</TEXT>

