<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Talks Held in Sevastopol on Fleet Dispute </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Talks Held in Sevastopol on Fleet Dispute </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204115394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1027 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2204115394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian and Ukrainian military officials have held 
further behind-the-scenes talks in Sevastopol in an effort to 
overcome the dispute over the Black Sea Fleet (BSF). Defence 
ministers Pavel Grachev and Vitaliy Radetskyy met privately 
before the two delegations went into a full-scale session. 
  Experts on both sides meeting later in the day on Thursday 
had failed to reach agreement on the location of the 
headquarters of Russian and Ukrainian parts of the Fleet, one 
negotiator told INTERFAX on condition of anonymity. 
  Ukraine wants to hold back to Sevastopol as its naval 
stronghold or share it together with Moscow. 
  The source believes that a sharing out of the Fleet is the 
only issue the two sides are most likely to resolve. He said 
Kiev might settle down for 18 pct of the BSF with the remainder 
going to Russia. 
  Presidents Yeltsin and Kravchuk meeting in Moscow a week ago 
had agreed that Ukraine's share of the Fleet would run at 15-20 
pct. 
  Moscow has remitted more than 250 billion karbovantsy for 
the 
upkeep of the Fleet this week though the April bill runs at 257 
billion, member of the Russian military delegation Vasiliy 
Vorobyev told INTERFAX. He said Kiev had stopped BSF financing 
since the end of last year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

