<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Insists on Signing Agreements With Latvia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Insists on Signing Agreements With Latvia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104213494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1817 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104213494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] During his telephone conversation with Latvia 
President Guntis Ulmanis Thursday, Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin confirmed that Moscow still insisted on signing the 
entire package of agreements on Russian troop withdrawal from 
Latvia. 
  The head of the Russian delegation to the talks with Latvia, 
Ambassador Sergey Zotov, told Interfax that the main 
Russian-Latvian treaty providing for the withdrawal date might 
be signed only if all the other three agreements, in the first 
place that on social guarantees for Russian military pensioners 
and their families residing in Latvia, were signed at the same 
time. 
  The Russian diplomat said that the summit could be held in 
the near future, as soon as Latvia was ready to sign all the 
four agreements at the same time. 
  The package includes the main treaty setting the withdrawal 
date as August 31, an agreement on the functioning of a radar 
station in Skrunda for another five and a half years, another 
one on social guarantees for Russian servicemen for the 
withdrawal period and the other one on social guarantees for 
Russian military pensioners. 
  The Latvian leadership declared its readiness to sign the 
first three documents, though it has been opposing the signing 
of the agreement on military pensioners. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

