<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rybkin Meets With Turkish Defense Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rybkin Meets With Turkish Defense Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204102994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1008 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2204102994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 24 -- The possibility of regulating 
conflicts in the Caucasus region and the Balkans is one of the 
many things which demands close cooperation between the Russian 
Federation and the Republic of Turkey, firmly declared Chairman 
of the Russian Duma Ivan Rybkin on Friday as he received 
Turkey's National Defence Minister Mehmet Gohlan. 
  According to the State Duma's press service, the speaker of 
the lower chamber of the Federal Assembly told his guest about 
the structure and work plans of the State Duma. 
  In turn, Gohlan expressed Turkey's interest in strengthening 
economic and military-technical ties between the two countries. 
The defence minister hoped to find in Moscow support and 
understanding of Turkey's efforts to solve its energy supply 
problems and desire to build heating and nuclear power plants. 
In addition, Turkey is looking to Russia for help in 
implementing a variety of projects concerning the transportation 
of energy resources from Russia to Turkey and transit through 
Turkey to other countries in the Mediterranean Sea area. 
  At the end of his meeting with the Turkish representative, 
Rybkin expressed his confidence that inter-parliamentary ties 
between the two countries would improve along with economic and 
military relations. He accepted Turkish parliamentary leader H. 
Cindoruk's invitation to visit Turkey at the head of an official 
parliamentary delegation from the Russian Federation. 

</TEXT>

