<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   'Arafat Sees `Differing' Views as Strength </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    'Arafat Sees `Differing' Views as Strength </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2104151694 Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA in Russian 21 Apr 
94 p 7 </F>

<F P=103> PM2104151694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Dmitriy Kulik and Sergey Postanogov article: "'Arafat Is </F>
Small But Smart"] 
  [Text] The visit to Moscow of Yasir 'Arafat, PLO Executive 
Committee chairman and president of the state of Palestine, has 
ended. 
  The main topic of the talks was, of course, the problem of 
the settlement in the Near East. 'Arafat emphasized that in 
spite of all the cosponsors' attempts to breath life into the 
Near East process, the peace negotiations have failed. The 
Israeli side is constantly maneuvering and trying to drag out 
the period for withdrawing its troops from the occupied 
territories, which, in his opinion, gives extremists from both 
sides opportunities to undermine the peace process for once and 
for all. If they succeed in doing this, the PLO leader stated, 
then complete anarchy and the region's Balkanization are 
inevitable. 
  On the subject of specific issues, it is necessary to point 
out that during the talks Boris Yeltsin gave instructions to 
prepare a Russian-Palestinian agreement on cultural cooperation. 
It is also not ruled out that the Russian side will assist in 
the formation and training of a police force in the future 
autonomous entity. 
  But the problem is, as we know, not only relations between 
the Palestinians and the Israelis but also the PLO's struggle 
with such extremist organizations as Hamas. In reply to our 
question about how 'Arafat intends to find a common language 
with the radicals if they continue to ignore the peace 
initiatives, he said that democracy presupposes the existence of 
various points of view. The PLO leader added that points of 
view differing from his own with regard to various problems were 
"not a weakness but a strength." 

</TEXT>

