<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Talks on Dniester To Resume Late Apr </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104183094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1611 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104183094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Demidetskiy] </F>
  [Text] Kishinev [Chisinau] 21 April TASS -- Talks on a 
peace settlement of the Dniester conflict consequences are to 
resume in Moldova in late April, the Russian president's special 
envoy for the talks Vladlen Vasev told TASS on Thursday. 
  According to Vasev, Russia's proposals for Dniester 
settlement are based on recommendations worked out by the CSCE 
mission in Moldova and take into account the interests of both 
sides to the conflict. 
  Dniester leader Igor Smirnov said yesterday Tiraspol found 
unacceptable some aspects of the Russian proposals. The 
document was also subjected to criticism by certain Moldovan 
politicians who assessed these proposals as "pro-Tiraspol." 
  "We believe our proposals can lay down the basis for 
negotiations," Russia's envoy stressed. "However, we are not 
too self-assured and understand they may be adjusted in the 
course of discussion in order to reflect the compromises 
reached," he noted. 

