<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official: Government Ready To Shut Down Chernobyl </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official: Government Ready To Shut Down Chernobyl </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104200094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1817 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104200094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Speaking to journalists in Kiev on Thursday, the 
first deputy chairman of the State Nuclear Energy Committee said 
that Ukraine is ready to shut down the Chernobyl nuclear power 
station. Nur Nigmatulin went on to say that before this happened 
more power stations would have to be built in order to make up 
the deficit. 
  He said that Ukraine would have to commission a total of six 
VVER reactors at the Khmelnitsky, Rovno and Zaporozhye nuclear 
stations. This would require a total of $1.02 billion. 
  On 21 April the third reactor at Chernobyl was brought on 
line again after the 18 April incident which registered one on 
the international scale. 
  On 18 April, the safety system at the third reactor was 
activated while power was being increased after routine repairs. 
This occurred after the water level in the cooling system fell. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

