<F P=100> Turkmenistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   First Round of Sino-Turkmen Talks End in Ashgabat </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    First Round of Sino-Turkmen Talks End in Ashgabat </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104173694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1608 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104173694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The first stage of talks between Chairman of the 
Chinese State Council Li Peng and Turkmenian President 
Saparmurad Niyazov ended in Ashkhabad [Ashgabat] on Thursday. 
The two sides discussed the possibilities of economic 
cooperation between the two countries. 
  Niyazov and Li Peng expressed interest in developing 
contacts 
in trade, light, fuel and energy and chemical industries, Head 
of the Information and Press Department of the Chinese Foreign 
Ministry Shen Guofang told a briefing of journalists in 
Ashkhabad on Thursday. In his words, "the signing of four-five 
intergovernmental agreements is possible" on 22 April, but 
"their texts are yet to be coordinated." 
  As INTERFAX learned from well-informed sources, the 
Turkmenian leadership is considering the proposal by the Chinese 
side to grant a credit worth 50 million yuan ($6 million). 
  The guests also suggested discussing the joint construction 
of two plants in Turkmenistan for the production of bricks and 
metallic items for seismo-proof building. 
  The two sides also discussed the possibility of building a 
gas pipeline Turkmenistan-China, but a representative of the 
Chinese Foreign Ministry said that this issue "was not discussed 
in detail, because the project demands specific preparation and 
technical and economic foundation." 
  The talks will continue on 22 April. 

</TEXT>

