<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   NATO General Comments at End of Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NATO General Comments at End of Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2104141194 Tallinn BNS in English 1213 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2104141194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Apr 21, BNS -- NATO Allied Forces in Europe 
North Military Group's Commander General Garry Johnson completed 
Thursday [21 April] his visit in Latvia. During the visit, he 
met with Latvian Defense Forces Commander Dainis Turlais, 
Defense Minister Valdis Pavlovskis and different ministry's 
officials, and Foreign Ministry's Parliamentarian Secretary 
Martins Virsis, and discussed Latvia's cooperation with NATO. 
  Before leaving, Johnson said at a press conference that the 
visit was done in the framework of NATO program for cooperation 
with other states. 
  Johnson noted that Latvian officers have taken part in 
several NATO training programs, and NATO expert groups help 
Latvian defense forces' representatives with advice. Johnson 
praised Turlais's contribution to the forming of Latvian defense 
forces. He noted that Latvian soldiers, sent to take part in 
NATO training programs, were physically well prepared. 
  Answering journalists' questions, Johnson said NATO was 
ready 
to cooperate both with Latvia and Russia, and he expressed hope 
that Russian army would be fully withdrawn from Latvia till the 
complete drafting of the cooperation program. He said Russian 
army's presence in Latvian Skrunda will not influence 
cooperation between Latvia and NATO, said Johnson. 
  Johnson also said that no priorities in cooperation with 
NATO 
would be given to Russia, though Russia could involve large 
forces in NATO's activities. 

</TEXT>

