<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnian Air Strikes To `Complicate' Situation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bosnian Air Strikes To `Complicate' Situation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204111794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1027 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2204111794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] There is every indication that events in and around 
Gorazde have entered a decisive stage. As a senior Russian 
Foreign Ministry official has reported to Interfax with 
reference to information from that city, hand-to-hand combat is 
underway there. 
  For this reason, NATO may decide already on Friday to back 
the UN Secretary General's request for massive air strikes on 
the Bosnian Serbs. However, such a decision could only escalate 
the conflict and give the Serbs freedom of action not only in 
Gorazde but elsewhere in Bosnia, the diplomat said. 
  In his words, NATO's massive air strikes might "seriously 
complicate" the position of peacekeepers in Bosnia and 
necessitate an evacuation of the Sarajevo-based Russian 
peace-keeping battalion. 
  He declined to say how precisely Russia would respond to 
massive air-strikes, if NATO mandated them. "There are a few 
options. Let us not spur on events," he noted. 
  He said that "this time Moscow cannot complain that it has 
not been consulted." Contacts with NATO and with Americans are 
underway at various levels. It is not ruled out that they will 
ultimately lead to a summit with Russia, US, EC, and UN to take 
part, on which Moscow has been insisting. It is hardly likely 
that efforts to prepare such a summit in just one month's time 
will succeed. As for a meeting at the foreign ministers level, 
it is not only feasible but necessary, the diplomat said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-17265 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov078_a_94002" </HT>


