<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Akayev Decrees Sacking of Finance Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Akayev Decrees Sacking of Finance Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104165694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1507 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104165694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: compiled by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy, edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] President Askar Akayev has decreed the removal of 
Finance Minister Kamchibek Shakirov for abuse of his official 
status and for issuing a loan from the state budget to a private 
firm. 
  The head of the president's press service Azim Ibraimov told 
INTERFAX that the finance minister's resignation was the first 
instance of an uncompromising decision with regard to a cabinet 
member. In his view, this was an example of the government's 
resolution to tighten state discipline over fiscal matters in 
use against officials who, regardless of their rank, had raised 
their own level of responsibility beyond that permissible by law. 
  Ibraimov pointed out that when the new premier Apas 
Dzhumagulov came to power, "the process of purging the state 
personnel system began in earnest." 
  He also said that K. Shakirov used his authority among 
government members "as a sufficiently well-versed and competent 
professional financier, who knew his business." However, 
"weakness of character led him to violate procedure and abuse 
his authorities and, succumbing to family loyalties, the finance 
minister issued a loan to his own son-in-law," Ibraimov said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

