<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia's Choice Chair on `Confrontation' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russia's Choice Chair on `Confrontation' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104210294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1817 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104210294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] If the opposition forces refuse to sign the treaty 
on Civil Accord, this will be a "political victory" for the 
democrats since society will see who is seeking accord and who 
confrontation. This statement was made by deputy chairman of the 
Russia's Choice faction, Boris Zolotukhin, at the faction's 
meeting. Russia's Choice leader Yegor Gaydar stated on behalf 
of the faction in the State Duma today that the faction was 
prepared to sign the document. 
  Russia's Choice member Yuliy Rybakov suggested that the 
State 
Duma would not give State Duma Speaker Ivan Rybkin a mandate for 
signing the agreement proposed by the president. Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP) leader, Vladimir Zhirinovskiy, has 
insisted that the State Duma take a vote on whether Rybkin be 
granted the right to sign the document on its behalf. 
Zolotukhin was certain that if the State Duma did not give the 
appropriate authority to Rybkin this would expose the Duma's 
majority as a force not seeking stabilization of the situation 
in society. 
  Deputy Bella Denisenko said the draft agreement provided for 
nothing except the idea of accord itself and the faction would 
have to sign just the title since there were no real moves 
towards accord mentioned in the document. She said that the 
document had already worsened the situation and brought 
different political forces into confrontation. 
  Former social security minister, Ella Pamfilova, recommended 
that the faction seriously speak to the president in the 
presence of all members of Russia's Choice. She said it was not 
clear what the president sought and in what the faction should 
back him and whether Boris Yeltsin needed this support. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

