<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nationalist `Accord' Elicits `Wide Response' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nationalist `Accord' Elicits `Wide Response' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2104103794 Moscow PRAVDA in Russian 20 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM2104103794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow PRAVDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Own Information" report: "Friends of `Accord'"] </F>
  [Text] The publication of an appeal by the initiators of 
the "Accord for Russia" movement has elicited a wide response in 
practically all parts of the Russian Federation. This is borne 
out by the mail addressed to Valeriy Zorkin, Gennadiy Zyuganov, 
Mikhail Lapshin, Aleksandr Rutskoy, Sergey Glazyev, and the 
other cofounders. They receive more than 500 individual and 
collective letters every day. 
  The call to unite patriotic forces has already been 
supported 
in official statements by more than 6,000 labor collectives, 
villagers, students, and even groups of senior pupils. They are 
all prepared actively to promote the movement's noble aims and 
to set up organizing subdivisions in the provinces. The ideas 
of accord and of strengthening the Russian State are becoming a 
consolidating factor for people of not only different ages but 
also professions and political orientations, even including 
voters who recently supported "Russia's Choice." 
  The largest number of proposals to set up "Accord for 
Russia" 
organizing groups has come from Altay and Krasnoyarsk Krays and 
Volgograd, Leningrad, Moscow, Nizhniy Novgorod, Novosibirsk, 
Samara, Saratov, Smolensk, and Chelyabinsk Oblasts. The 
movement's ideas have also been supported in the Russian 
Federation republics. The influential public organization 
"Citizens of Mordovia for Social Justice, Legality, and Economic 
Stability" plans to examine the question of joining the movement 
at its next congress. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

