<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shokhin To Implement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shokhin To Implement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2104150494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1127 GMT 21 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2104150494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On Thursday Russian Prime Minister Viktor 
Chernomyrdin reported at the sitting of the Cabinet's presidium 
that the government had received a letter from the president 
which contains direct instructions regarding the situation in 
the state economy and in the country as a whole. Chernomyrdin 
noted that "the president's concern is not ungrounded" and "his 
attitude towards the instructions of the head of the Russian 
state is always a very serious one." 
  In Chernomyrdin's words, the document received from Yeltsin 
was already considered on April 19 and the issues defined in it 
would be solved in the near term. Chernomyrdin reported that 
Vice Premier and Economics Minister Aleksandr Shokhin had been 
commissioned to fulfill the president's instructions. 
  The sitting of the government's presidium approved the 
principal trends of the Cabinet's social policy for 1994. The 
social policy gives priorities to the following: prevention of 
any lowering of the population's level of incomes, preserving of 
the balance between economic interests and material 
opportunities of three major population groups: hired workers, 
entrepreneurs, and disabled citizens. 
  To this effect Chernomyrdin indicated that the tax reform to 
which he pays the greatest significance is to be the key element 
of the social policy. In his words, "taxes should not bring 
damage to people." 
  The government's presidium returned for revision the draft 
of 
the federal program on assistance in the population's employment 
in 1994 prepared by the Federal Employment Service. As 
Chernomyrdin said, the document does not properly point out 
measures for helping in the employment of those who graduate 
from educational institutions, does not take into consideration 
investment programs the implementation of which the unemployed 
can be involved. A governmental commission headed by Vice 
Premier Yuriy Yarov has been formed to revise the federal 
program. 

</TEXT>

