<F P=100> RUSSIAN NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation Council Begins Discussion of Draft </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Federation Council Begins Discussion of Draft </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2504101194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0924 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2504101194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 25 TASS -- The Federation Council has 
begun to discuss the draft treaty on civic concord. Previously 
President Yeltsin sent a note to Vladimir Shumeyko, which 
expressed hope that the Federation Council would manage to 
prepare the text of the treaty for signing. Yeltsin appealed to 
"the wisdom of deputies and their understanding of common 
responsibility before Russian citizens." 
  Academician Boris Topornin, official representative of the 
Russian president and co-chairman of the public chamber, told 
the deputies that the draft treaty was the result of collective 
work and was approved by the majority of members of the working 
group, which prepared it. "The provisions, that contradict each 
other, were not included in the text, because it is going to be 
a document of concord," he explained. 
  Topornin stressed that the country cannot overcome the 
economic crisis without political stability. Authors of the 
draft treaty wanted it to be "neither a party, or group 
document, but a document reflecting common interests." The 
treaty will neither amend nor replace the Constitution and other 
legal acts. 
  According to Topornin, the item on responsibility for the 
non- fulfilment of the treaty was removed from the draft 
document, because "it cannot be based on enforcement and 
sanctions... Public control and the attitude of the population 
to it are the most reliable guarantee of its fulfilment," 
Topornin said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-17325 </DOCNO>
