<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko Speaks Out Against Early Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shumeyko Speaks Out Against Early Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2304174194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1322 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2304174194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Federation Council's Speaker Vladimir Shumeyko 
has spoken out against early presidential elections in Russia. 
  He wished that Boris Yeltsin would not only carry on as 
president until 1996 but would nominate himself to next 
presidential elections and be elected for yet another five-year 
term. 
  Talking to the editors-in-chief of Russia's leading media, 
Shumeyko said that Boris Yeltsin is the only appropriate 
candidate to the presidency in the country. 
  "A change of Russian president now would be tantamount to a 
catastrophe, he believes. A new head of state would start 
changing the entire team in the center and province. His people 
would start settling scores with previous teammates." 
  In such an event, Shumeyko feels, Russia would plunge into 
such a political and economic crisis that would blast any hope 
for further reform. 

</TEXT>

