<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Abolishes Blacklist of Deputies </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Abolishes Blacklist of Deputies </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204144394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1315 
GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2204144394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow 22 Apr -- Boris Yeltsin today cancelled his 
edict "On Not Extending State Guarantees of Social Protection To 
Certain Former People's Deputies of the Russian Federation." 
This was the edict issued on 6 October 1993, enabling 
Presidential Administration Head Sergey Filatov and a special 
commission to draw up a list of 151 deputies to be deprived of 
the payment of one year's salary based on the salary they were 
paid in their final month as deputy. This sum amounts to about 
3-4 million rubles and is being paid to each black listed deputy 
from the state budget. 
  The issue of whether they should be allowed to keep the 
Moscow flats they were allocated when working for the Supreme 
Soviet is also still being debated. But on the eve of the 
signing of the treaty on civil accord, the president has decided 
to meet the opposition half way in order to achieve civil peace 
in Russia. 

</TEXT>

