<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Supports Live Broadcast of Debates </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Supports Live Broadcast of Debates </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204135794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1302 
GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2204135794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 22 Apr -- Boris Yeltsin has backed the State 
Duma's decision on granting live broadcast time to the various 
political forces for discussion of the treaty on the attainment 
of civic accord in Russia. He announced this in the Kremlin 
today at a working conference of those participating in the 
agreement on the attainment of civic accord in Russia. 
  "Russia has an alternative to confrontation," Boris Yeltsin 
declared. According to him, the document on civic accord that 
has been prepared "is an agreement of which all the social and 
political forces are the authors." 
  The president noted that "each side will commit itself to 
implementing the treaty; everyone will have to give up 
something." "Calm in Russia is the main thing; for the sake of 
that, one must impose limitations on oneself and find a salutary 
compromise." 
  Boris Yeltsin is certain that "the country is badly in need 
of a new political culture." In his opinion, a permanently 
operating mechanism for accord must be devised. Analysing the 
draft agreement that was achieved, Boris Yeltsin noted that all 
political and social forces needed to prove in practice that 
"extremism is ineffective in politics." 

</TEXT>

