<F P=100> RUSSIAN NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Speed Up Agricultural Reform </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government To Speed Up Agricultural Reform </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2404163994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1534 GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2404163994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] This year, the Russian government is planning to 
accelerate agricultural reform and develop a procedure of 
agricultural enterprises' bankruptcy, Russia's Vice Premier 
Aleksandr Zaveryukha told Interfax. 
  He said that in the first quarter of 1994, agricultural 
production decreased by 13 percent and that no signs of 
stabilization were being felt. More than 30 percent of 
collective and state farms, and joint-stock societies do not 
earn enough to pay wages to the workers, said Zaveryukha. 
  He noted, however, that the government's attempts to 
privatize loss-making collective farms according to the Nizhnyy 
Novgorod or Moscow models, were resisted. 
  He confirmed the government's determination to observe the 
voluntary principle of privatizing large state-run and 
collective farms, and announced that the president and the prime 
minister had categorically rejected the proposal by head of the 
president's analytical center Petr Filippov on compulsory 
privatization of state and collective farms. 

</TEXT>

