<F P=100> RUSSIAN NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Increase Efforts To Find Tax Dodgers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Police Increase Efforts To Find Tax Dodgers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2304135994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1344 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2304135994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Lyudmila Yermakova and Igor </F>
Galkin] 
  [Text] Moscow April 23 TASS -- Russian tax police reported 
32,000 violations of tax legislation in 1993 and over 10,000 in 
the first quarter of 1994. 
  The figures were cited at a session of the Federation 
Council, upper house of the parliament, on Saturday. 
  Members of the House Budget Committee stressed that "tax 
privileges have failed to act as a stimulant for industry and in 
many cases have been used for dodging taxes." 
  In 1993 tax inspectors discovered over 1,000 unregistered 
legal entities which did not pay any taxes. They instituted 
criminal proceedings on more than 600 cases and about 200 in the 
first three months of 1994. They also stressed that more and 
more often tax inspectors become objects of assaults. 
  Tax revenues could increase the federal budget by billions 
of 
roubles, tax police officials said. Last year inspections and 
raids helped recover additional 800 billion roubles and over 600 
billion in the first quarter of 1994. 
  Officials complained that the tax system is in "complete 
chaos." Non-payment of income tax and value added tax accounts 
for the bulk of all tax violations. Enterprises often report 
bigger costs of their products than they actually are in order 
to avoid paying taxes. 
  Tax police experts believe only five major taxes should be 
left in Russia -- real estate tax, income tax for individuals 
and businesses, value added tax and excise tax. They 
recommended replacing profit tax with company income tax. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

