<H3> <TI>   Solution Sought for Submarine Yard's Nuclear Waste </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Solution Sought for Submarine Yard's Nuclear Waste </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2304163894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1025 
GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2304163894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Larisa Beloivan and Leonid </F>
Vinogradov] 
  [Text] Vladivostok, 23 Apr -- Russia does not yet have the 
resources to build purification installations, but the problem 
of utilizing waste from nuclear submarines must be tackled 
immediately, said Yuriy Maslakov, the director of the Zvezda 
nuclear submarine repair yard, at a briefing devoted to the 
completion of Russo- Japanese consultations on utilizing nuclear 
waste. 
  Nikolay Yegorov, Russian deputy minister of atomic energy, 
who attended the consultations, told journalists that there were 
three possible solutions to the problem: Build a purification 
complex on the territory of the yard itself; set up the same 
system in an isolated area of the Maritime Kray; or introduce 
advanced purification plants. As has already been reported, 
Russia and Japan have signed an agreement on an allocation by 
the Japanese side of $70 million toward converting Russia's arms 
enterprises. There are plans to use part of this money at the 
Zvezda yard. 

</TEXT>

