<F P=100> RUSSIAN NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko Offers Longer Service for Warrant Officers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shumeyko Offers Longer Service for Warrant Officers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2304142494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1319 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2304142494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 23 TASS -- Russian Federation Council 
Chairman Vladimir Shumeyko has suggested extending military 
service for warrant officers for another five to ten years with 
their consent. 
  Shumeyko sent a draft law "on military duty and military 
service" to the State Duma chairman on Saturday. 
  "There is a shortage of warrant officer specialists in the 
Russian Armed Forces," Shumeyko explained. At present, warrant 
officers retire at the age of 45. After retirement from the 
army, many of them start looking for a job in the civilian 
sector whose employees themselves are facing redundancy claims. 
  Extended military service up to 55 years for warrant 
officers 
could help partially ease the problem, provided they want to 
stay in the army, Shumeyko said. 

</TEXT>

