<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cooperation With Chinese Businessmen To Increase </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cooperation With Chinese Businessmen To Increase </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2404210394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2004 GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2404210394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correpondent Boris Mainayev] </F>
  [Text] Bishkek 25 April TASS -- Business people of China 
and the Central Asian Republic of Kirgizia [Kyrgyzstan] plan to 
step up mutually beneficial cooperation. Participants in the 
meeting of Kirgiz and Chinese entrepreneurs, which was timed to 
coincide with the visit by Chinese State Council Premier Li Peng 
to Kirgizia this weekend, came to the conclusion that each 
industry in the economies of both countries were of certain 
mutual interest. 
  Kirgiz businessmen expressed readiness to supplement the 
list 
of the already existing 75 joint ventures with new ones, which 
will use Chinese technologies in food-making, processing of 
animal farming produce, manufacture of medicines and in 
agriculture. In their turn, Chinese entrepreneurs are 
interested in joint development of economic minerals, production 
of building materials, construction of roads to connect Kirgizia 
and China. 
  The meeting revealed certain differences between the Kirgiz 
and Chinese business people. Thus, the Chinese side would like 
to purchase Kirgiz electricity at prices close to the internal 
ones, while Kirgizia intends to raise them up to the level of 
world prices. But all these problems are quite solvable as long 
as entrepreneurs of the two countries are ready to meet each 
other halfway, participants in the meeting noted. 
  The meeting resulted in signing five protocols of intent, 
which are to be put into actions as soon as certain concrete 
projects are elaborated. 
  Last year's trade turnover between China and Kirgizia 
exceeded 100 mln dollars. According to the State Council 
premier, this figure is likely to be doubled this year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

