<F P=100> Turkmenistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Accords Signed at End of Tajik, PRC Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Accords Signed at End of Tajik, PRC Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204122894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1055 
GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2204122894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Glazovskaya] </F>
  [Text] Ashkhabad [Ashgabat], 22 Apr -- The Turkmen-Chinese 
summit talks have ended with the signing of three 
intergovernmental and five interdepartmental agreements in 
Ashkhabad. Agreements have been reached on the provision by 
China of a state loan of 50 million yuan to Turkmenistan, on 
cooperation between the Foreign Ministries of the two countries, 
and also on the study by inhabitants of the two countries of the 
Chinese and Turkmen languages. 
  Letters of intents have been signed: 

  -  Between the Ministry of Oil and Gas of Turkmenistan and 
the Chinese national oil and gas company on joint cooperation in 
the development of the two countries' oil and gas 
sectors; 
  -  Between the Turkmen "Kuvvat" state power technology 
corporation and a Chinese trade and industry group of companies, 
in which the Chinese side has expressed willingness to build an 
iron and steel works to process scrap metal and an aluminum 
production works; 
  -  On long-term cooperation between the Ministry 
of Construction and Architecture of Turkmenistan and the 
all-China engineering and construction corporation, which 
expresses willingess to cooperate on the setting up of joint 
enterprises to produce welding electrodes, porcelain goods, 
ceramic tiles, earthenware, and furniture. 
  -  A letter of intent 
between the Ministry of Trade of Turkmenistan and a Chinese 
electronics import and export company envisages reciprocal 
commercial activity; in particular, deliveries by the Chinese 
company of domestic electronic equipment and electronic goods. 
  -  A 
letter of intent between the Ministry of Agriculture of 
Turkmenistan and the "Chinatex" textile import and export 
company of China reflects a willingness by the Chinese side to 
purchase Turkmen cotton fiber. 

</TEXT>

