<F P=100> Turkmenistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Niyazov, Li Peng Agree to Chinese Aid </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Niyazov, Li Peng Agree to Chinese Aid </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204220094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1407 
GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2204220094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Ashkhabad [Ashgabat], 22 Apr -- Turkmen President 
Saparmurad Niyazov and Li Peng, premier of the State Council of 
the People's Republic of China (PRC), have agreed to expand 
bilateral, political, economic, and cultural links. 
  After completing his three-day visit to Turkmenistan, the 
Chinese governmental head left for Bishkek where he will have 
talks with Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev on Saturday [23 April]. 
  Although during the visit no agreement was concluded on the 
"project of the century" -- the installation with Chinese 
participation of a super gas pipe to connect wells in the 
Karakum deserts to gas rings on the islands of Japan -- the 
parties agreed to "continue to study seriously" the project. A 
protocol on intentions was signed between Turkmenistan's 
Ministry of Oil and Gas and the Chinese national oil corporation 
that envisages the creation of a Sino-Turkmen-Japanese 
commission of experts. 
  In the opinion of experts, Turkmenistan may boost its yearly 
gas extraction to 230 billion cubic meters in the next 15 years. 
  A press communique on the visit's results distributed by the 
Chinese delegation notes both countries' intention to build 
long- term, stable relations on the basis of principles of world 
coexistence emphasized at the talks. The Chinese Government 
voiced support for Turkmenistan's efforts to defend state 
independence and sovereignty and to stabilize the situation in 
the country and region. Direct links between the partners in 
the trading and economic sphere would be encouraged. There was 
a "positive attitude" to opening direct air links between China 
and Turkmenistan. 
  An agreement on granting Turkmenistan a Chinese loan and a 
protocol on regular consultations between the two countries' 
foreign ministries were signed in the presidential palace today. 
The Chinese Government will also grant material and technical 
assistance free of charge. Both the contents of the latter and 
the value of the loan are unknown. 
  Li Peng, who has already been to Uzbekistan, will also visit 
Kazakhstan and Mongolia in the course of his present 12-day 
trip. 

</TEXT>

