<DOCNO> FBIS4-17403 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov079_d_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-079 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Electricity Supply to Chechnya Normal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Electricity Supply to Chechnya Normal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204162994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1306 
GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2204162994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Ivantsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 22 Apr -- Supplies of electricity from 
Russia to Chechnya have not been halted. Electricity is being 
supplied to Chechnya as before, an ITAR-TASS correspondent was 
told today by Fedor Morozov, head of the central control room of 
the Yedinaya Energosistema Rossii Russian shareholding company. 
He said 50 MW of electricity is reaching Chechnya from Russia 
hourly. 
  Russian power engineering people did not register any 
alterations to these parameters today. Fedor Morozov thinks 
that it is so far impossible to understand the reason behind the 
recent reports that electricity supplies to Chechnya were cut 
off, since at about 1100 Moscow Time the central control room's 
communications with Chechnya went down and it has not been found 
possible to restore them. It cannot be ruled out that several 
customers may have been cut off, but a decision of this kind 
could only have been made by Chechnya's local power grid. 

</TEXT>

