<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Confers With UN Secretary General </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister Confers With UN Secretary General </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2204163394 Tallinn BNS in English 1005 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2204163394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Apr 22, BNS -- Estonian Prime Minister 
Mart Laar, who is on an official visit to the United States, met 
yesterday with the U.N. Secretary General Butros Butros-Ghali. 
  Butros-Ghali was pleased with Estonia's participation in the 
formation of the Baltic peacekeeping battalion. He promised his 
assistance to Estonia, if needed, in issues related to the 
withdrawal of Russian troops from the country. Butros-Ghali 
said the United Nations attaches great importance to forging 
ties with new member states. 
  Laar informed the U.N. secretary general about the recent 
International Labor Organization anniversary conference in 
Tallinn and Estonians' participation in peacekeeping missions in 
the Nordic countries' peacekeeping units. 
  The Estonian premier also gave a survey of Estonia's recent 
history, the reforms in society and the problems related to the 
continued presence of Russian troops in the country, such as 
increase in troop-related crime, enormous damage to the 
environment, and the danger posed by the Paldiski nuclear 
reactors. 
  Laar touched briefly on the general need to take into 
account 
and protect the interests of small countries, especially with a 
view to their security. 
  The U.N. secretary general affirmed that the organization 
represents the interests of all its member states. He 
underscored the importance of the participation of an Estonian 
delegation in the upcoming U.N. conferences and summit meetings. 
  Laar continued his visit to the United States in Boston. He 
talked at Harvard University about Estonian economy. 
  The Estonian premier is accompanied by Foreign Ministry 
Chancellor Indrek Tarand, his private secretary Toomas Kiho and 
adviser to the government Ardo Hansson. 
  Laar returns to Estonia on April 25. 

</TEXT>

