<H3> <TI>   Legislative Foreign Affairs Commissions Meet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Legislative Foreign Affairs Commissions Meet </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2204163194 Tallinn ETA in English 0819 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2204163194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn ETA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From 22 April EESTI SENUMID, PAEVALEHT, p 1; "News </F>
Bulletin" No. 77/94] 
  [Text] Friday, April 22 -- Representatives of 
parliamentary foreign affairs commissions of eleven countries 
met in Tallinn yesterday to discuss their role in the shaping of 
foreign policy. 
  The commission chairmen meeting held a news conference 
yesterday, describing the issued discussed and the results of 
the meeting. Chairman of the Riigikogu [parliament] foreign 
affairs commission and initiator of the meeting Vello Saatpalu 
described the topics as the making of foreign policy by the 
different arms of power, the technology of foreign policy and 
the role of traditions and laws. Estonia has an excellent 
opportunity to take over the best experience of existing 
systems, he stressed. 
  Riigikogu Vice-chairman Tunne Kelam pointed out that 
representatives of various political systems were represented, 
enabling to learn about different foreign political traditions. 
  Saatpalu criticised some examples of Estonia's recent past 
when vital decisions had been made without involving all the 
relevant institutions and cited the example of Russia where the 
positions of the president, the foreign minister and the defence 
minister can widely differ. He hoped that such meetings will 
become regular. 
  Foreign Minister Juri Luik and Tunne Kelam met Chairman of 
the Swedish parliamentary foreign affairs commission Daniel 
Tarschys, who was recently elected new Secretary General of the 
Council of Europe [CE]. They discussed the future of the CE and 
the Estonian-Russian relations. Tarschys stressed that Russia 
will have to meet the CE requirements before joining the 
organisation, including the one allowing member states to keep 
their troops in other countries only with the consent of these 
countries. 

</TEXT>

