<H3> <TI>   Aliyev Calls Russia's Position on Unclear </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Aliyev Calls Russia's Position on Unclear </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2304162794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1425 
GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2304162794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Sevindzh Abdullayev and Viktor </F>
Shulman] 
  [Text] Baku, 23 Apr -- Azerbaijani President Geydar Aliyev 
and Sergey Baburin, the head of a Russian State Duma delegation 
and coordinator of the deputy's group Russian Path, who met 
today in Baku, spoke out in favor of restoring, developing, and 
strengthening ties between Azerbaijan and Russia. 
  On the issue of the situation of Russians in Azerbaijan, the 
president stressed that they are and always have been an 
integral part of society, citizens of the republic with full 
rights. He said that "Azerbaijan's multi-ethnicity, its 
different languages, and use of Russian in many spheres have 
played an important role in the development and making of the 
culture of the people of Azerbaijan." 
  Geydar Aliyev familiarized the Russian parliamentarians with 
the current situation in the conflict zone between Armenia and 
Azerbaijan. He said that Azerbaijan was making efforts toward a 
peaceful settlement of the conflict, but that the republic's 
interests have to be taken into account. Russia, in whom 
Azerbaijan holds great hopes, has not yet adopted a position in 
principle on this issue, he believes. 
  The leader of Azerbaijan believes that some progress in the 
peacekeeping process could be made if Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin were to visit the region. He said that this was 
proposed to the Russian leader and that Azerbaijan are ready to 
provide for his security during his stay here. 

</TEXT>

