<DOCNO> FBIS4-17437 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov079_r_94008" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-079 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Turkish Foreign Minister Cetin on Baku Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Turkish Foreign Minister Cetin on Baku Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Cetin Urges Sanctions on Armenia </H4>

<F P=102> LD2404205594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2033 GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2404205594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Sevindzh Abdullayeva and Viktor </F>
Shulman] 
  [Text] Baku April 25 TASS -- Three-hour talks between 
Turkish Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin and Azeri President Geydar 
Aliyev were completed here late at night on Sunday. The meeting 
was mostly held behind closed doors. 
  The talks were focused on the Armenian-Azeri conflict over 
the disputed Nagorno-Karabakh enclave and ways for its 
settlement. According to the Azeri leader, efforts by 
international organizations, including the United Nations, the 
CSCE and its Minsk group, failed to produce any positive 
results. Seeking to end the protracted warfare by any means, 
the republic accepted Russia's mediatory initiatives. However, 
all attempts to solve the thorny problem have been in vain so 
far. The only obvious thing is that the Armenian side is 
forcing Azerbaijan to agree to its terms, which do not meet the 
republic's national interests, Aliyev emphasised. 
  The Turkish foreign minister believes that "the world 
community should at last understand clearly that Azerbaijan is 
forced to wage war in order to defend its territories." Cetin 
dismissed the principle of equal responsibility of both 
conflicting sides for the continued fighting, since "aggression 
is aimed against Azerbaijan." He pledged that "Turkey would 
uphold this position at all international forums." 
  The Turkish foreign minister told a news conference after 
the 
talks that "Armenia should meet the demands of U.N. Security 
Council resolutions, and to withdraw its troops from occupied 
Azeri lands immediately and unconditionally." In case it 
continues ignoring these demands, the world community should 
impose sanctions upon the republic, Cetin stressed. As for 
Turkey, it will not lift the embargo for supplies of foodstuffs 
and medicines to Armenia until the republic halts the aggression 
against Azerbaijan. 
  According to the Turkish foreign minister, the current 
deadlock in the peace process can be broken by convening a 
session of the Minsk conference. However, this is possible only 
in case of liberation of Azeri territories. Therefore, Russia, 
the United States and other Minsk group countries should step up 
their efforts to create conditions for the session to be 
convened. 
  Speaking about deployment of peacekeeping troops in the 
conflict zone, Cetin emphasised that "Turkey strongly believes 
these can be only international forces, not troops of any 
definite country." 
  The Turkish foreign minister assessed his short-term visit 
to 
the Azeri capital Baku as "very fruitful." According to his 
Azeri counterpart Hasan Hasanov, this visit testified to 
Azerbaijan's stable and consistent relations with Turkey, to 
which the republic gives top priority in its foreign policy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-17438 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov079_r_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-079 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Update on Situation at Front </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Update on Situation at Front </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2304111294 Baku TURAN in English 0910 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2304111294 </F>
<F P=104>  Baku TURAN </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Baku (April 22) TURAN -- Last night Armenian troops 
continued attacking along the entire frontline, reports the 
press centre of Azerbaijan Defense Ministry. 
  The Armenian army attacked the southern section of the front 
(Fizuli-Beylagan) three times. The Azeri army managed to 
liberate the village of Ashagy-Abdurakhmanly and several 
strategically important heights. During the fighting three of 
Armenia's tanks and one military personnel carrier were 
destroyed and several dozens of Armenian soldiers were killed. 
The Azeri army captured five machine-guns, one flame-thrower 
cluster, four grenade discharger cups, and dozens of sub-machine 
guns. 
  Fierce fighting in the eastern direction (Agdam-Terter) of 
the front took place throughout the night where the Armenian 
army tried to break through the defense of the Azeri army. But 
attempts by the Armenian army failed since the Azeri army was 
subject to fire upon the position of Armenian troops in this 
direction. Approximately 50 Armenian soldiers were killed in 
this section of the front. 
  This morning the Armenian army fired upon the village of 
Tap-Karakayully of the Geranboy region. 
  At the same times border posts of the Azeri army in the 
Tauzskiy region were subjected to fire from the Idzhevanskiy 
region of Armenia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
