<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Delay in Sending Troops to Abkhazia Criticized </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UN Delay in Sending Troops to Abkhazia Criticized </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2304211194 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1920 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2304211194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Another round of Georgian-Abkhaz talks held last 
week in Geneva still did not produce any tangible results. 
Although the fact that the talks are being held at all is in 
itself a positive development. The Georgian side's position on 
the return of refugees to Galskiy Rayon remains unchanged: Their 
safety has to be ensured. As for Abkhazia's political status, 
the United Nations has produced a document on setting up a 
coordinating council, which is to operate until the conflict is 
completely settled. 
  It has also become known that Jaba Ioseliani, head of the 
Georgian delegation, has expressed resentment with the stand 
taken by the United Nations, which decided not to send its 
peacekeeping contingent to the area until this August. 
According to Ioseliani, it is quite possible that Georgia will 
accept the proposal put forward by the Russian Federation, which 
offered to send its forces to Abkhaz territory as soon as 
possible. 
  But in the view of Aleksandr Kavsadze, the head of state's 
personal envoy for the settlement of the conflict, all 
prerequisites exist even now for the UN Security Council to make 
a decision to deploy international peacekeeping forces on the 
entire territory of Abkhazia. 

</TEXT>

