<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abkhazian Deputy Kakubava Abducted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Abkhazian Deputy Kakubava Abducted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2304142194 Tbilisi IBERIA in Georgian 1315 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2304142194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi IBERIA </F>
<F P=105>  Georgian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tbilisi, 23 Apr -- At nine o'clock yesterday Boris 
Kakubava, a deputy in the Georgian parliament and chairman of 
the Abkhazian Liberation Union, was abducted after he had taken 
part in an Alioni program on Georgian television. 
  Threatening to execute him, the kidnappers demanded that 
Boris Kakubava cancel the congress of the displaced Abkhazian 
population scheduled to he held in Tbilisi 23-25 April. The 
organizers of the terrorist act seem to be afraid that the 
congress could make the Georgian leaders' political course on 
the Abkhazian issue look negative. A probable tragic end has 
been prevented by the prompt intervention of the Abkhazian 
Liberation Union. 
  This, as well as other events (delegates of the congress 
have 
been denied transport by rayon authorities; transport routes 
have been closed), demonstrates a desire of the authorities to 
prevent the congress. 
  The Abkhazian Liberation Union places the entire 
responsibility for the incident and its consequences on the 
leadership of the Republic of Georgia. 
  This statement was made public by the press service of the 
Abkhazian Liberation Union at a news conference in Tbilisi on 23 
April. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

