<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continuation of Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Continuation of Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Zlenko Warns Talks Could Stall </H4>

<F P=102> LD2204104694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0945 
GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2204104694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Blagov] </F>
  [Text] Hanoi, 22 Apr (ITAR-TASS) -- The presidents of 
Russia and Ukraine have agreed that a friendship and cooperation 
treaty between the two countries must be drafted in the near 
future. This was stated in an ITAR-TASS interview today by 
Ukrainian Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko who is paying an 
official visit to Hanoi. At their meeting in Moscow on 15 April 
the Russian and Ukrainian presidents instructed their foreign 
ministers to complete the preparation of the draft treaty. In 
this connection Leonid Kravchuk invited Boris Yeltsin, president 
of the Russian Federation, to pay an official state visit to 
Ukraine. The invitation was accepted. We hope that the 
interstate treaty will be signed during this visit, the 
Ukrainian foreign minister said. 
  Referring to the talks in Sevastopol between the Russian and 
Ukrainian defense ministers, A. Zlenko stressed that "the 
decisions adopted at the April meeting of the two presidents 
must be carried out." The accords already reached on dividing 
up the fleet and separate basing of the two countries' naval 
forces must be implemented. By adhering to these accords, 
without backing away from them, we can make progress toward a 
solution of the Black Sea Fleet problem. If, however, attempts 
to reinterpret the decisions made by the two presidents 
continue, I think we will again find ourselves deadlocked as we 
try to settle this "extremely complex" question, A. Zlenko noted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

