<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continuation of Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Continuation of Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    No Agreement Reached on Bases </H4>

<F P=102> LD2204131294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1240 
GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2204131294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS special correspondent Mikhail Shevtsov] </F>
  [Text] Sevastopol, 22 Apr -- An agreement in principle to 
divide the Black Sea Fleet was reached today at the talks 
between the military delegations of Russia and the Ukraine in 
Sevastopol. They were led by the two countries' defense 
ministers, Pavel Grachev and Vitaliy Radetskyy. 
  Of the 833 Black Sea Fleet ships and vessels, 669 units will 
go to Russia, which makes up nearly 85 percent. The Ukrainian 
side will receive 164 ships and boats (15 percent). Moreover, 
proceeding from the previously reached accords, Russia will pay 
the Ukraine compensation for 255 vessels. 
  No agreement has yet been reached on the problem of the 
separate basing of the fleets. Ukraine insists on siting the 
headquarters of its navy in Sevastopol, and does not rule out 
the basing of its ships there as well. 
  Army General Pavel Grachev, Russian defense minister, 
stressed that this stance deviates from the agreement signed on 
15 April in Moscow by Boris Yeltsin and Leonid Kravchuk. 
  The Russian minister declared that it is unlikely that a 
start can be made on dividing up the fleet without resolving the 
problem of the separate bases. 
  Pavel Grachev left Sevastopol for Moscow today. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-17460 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov079_e_94008" </HT>


