<DATE1>  22 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continuation of Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Continuation of Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Foreign Ministry Spokesman on `Difficulties' </H4>

<F P=102> LD2204154594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1404 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2204154594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] At the talks in Sevastopol Friday on the division of 
the Black Sea Fleet, the military delegations of Russia and 
Ukraine came to an agreement on the Fleet's division. In an 
exclusive interview to INTERFAX Ukranian Defense Minister 
Vitaliy Radetskyy said that 18.3 percent of the Fleet, or 164 
warships and other vessels, are to be handed over to Ukraine. 
  Radetskyy said that he had reported to President Kravchuk 
about the decision and the Ukrainian president backed it. 
Radetskyy said that Russia was ready to pay for the Ukrainian 
part of the fleet after it was divided 50-50. However, it is up 
to the governments to decide how payment should be effected, he 
said. 
  Radetskyy also said that Russia decided on which ships it 
needed proceeding from the tasks faced by the Black Sea Fleet. 
The remaining vessels will be written-off or sold, he said. 
  Earlier, spokesman for the Ukrainian Defense Ministry, 
Aleksandr Kluban, told reporters that the split up would affect 
833 warships on active duty and 61 reserve ships. Out of this 
number 18.3 percent or 164 ships will belong to Ukraine. The 
remaining 31.7 percent of ships out of Ukraine's 50 percent are 
to be sold to Russia, in line with the earlier agreements. 
  Ukraine, said the spokesman, proposes that the matter should 
be settled by the signing of an agreement. The draft agreement 
is ready and will possibly be signed on 22 April. 
  Radetskyy said that still unresolved is the issue of bases 
for the Black Sea Fleet and the Ukrainian naval force. He said 
that both Ukraine and Russia have proposals on that score. He 
believes that the delegations should not leave Sevastopol 
without solving the problem. 
  Meanwhile, Kluban said that there are difficulties in 
discussing the issue. Russia proposes to base its fleet at all 
Crimean bases (Sevastopol, Balaklava, Kerch, Donuzlav and 
Feodosiya). Moscow is flatly against the deployment of the 
Ukrainian naval force in the Crimea, said the spokesman. This 
is unacceptable for us, he said. 
  The spokesman also said that the Ukrainian leadership will 
elevate the cash allowance for seamen of the Ukrainian fleet to 
be equal to that of the Black Sea Fleet officers. 
  Kluban said that the problems associated with naval aviation 
were not discussed. 
  An Interfax correspondent reports from Sevastopol that on 
Friday, later in the day, the Russian and Ukrainian defense 
ministers, Pavel Grachev and Vitaliy Radetskyy, are to sign an 
agreement which will fix parameters for the fleet's division. 
Experts who are drafting the document doubt that the 
delegations in Sevastopol will manage to solve the issue 
surrounding bases for the Black Sea Fleet and the Ukrainian 
naval force. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-17461 </DOCNO>
