<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continuation of Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Continuation of Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kravchuk on Ships in Sevastopol </H4>

<F P=102> LD2204164994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1404 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2204164994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Leonid Kravchuk told newsmen after the 
Ukrainian parliament closed session in Kiev, that both a Russian 
and Ukrainian presence in Sevastopol offered the best solution 
for the problem of the Black Sea Fleet. 
  However, Kravchuk felt the Russian and Ukrainian vessels 
must 
use different naval facilities. The Ukrainian fleet could be 
based in Balaklava. 
  Kravchuk said he kept in touch with the Ukrainian delegation 
to the Sevastopol negotiations. He said the Russian and 
Ukrainian Defense ministers had agreed on a formula for the 
solution of the existing problems on the basis of the Yalta, 
Zavidovo and Massandra decisions. 
  In Kravchuk's view, both the Russian and Ukrainian fleets 
must make use of Sevastopol's repair docks given that 82 percent 
of the Black Sea's infrastructure is in that city. 
  If, however, the two Defense ministers failed to reach 
agreement, Kravchuk said he would meet to resolve the problem 
with his Russian counterpart Boris Yeltsin. The problem of the 
Black Sea Fleet is to be resolved at any cost, said Kravchuk. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

