<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continuation of Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Continuation of Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kravchuk Refutes Grachev's Statement </H4>

<F P=102> LD2504104694 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
1000 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2504104694 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukraine's President Leonid Kravchuk refuted the 
statement by Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev about the 
intentions of our state to review the accords on the division of 
the Black Sea Fleet. The last meeting of the defense ministers 
of Ukraine and Russia in Crimea was of a working nature and 
cannot be a final evaluation of the division of the Black Sea 
Fleet, Leonid Kravchuk told journalists. The statement by 
Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev to the Ostankino 
television company that Ukraine has changed its stand is 
groundless, he emphasized. 
  Leonid Kravchuk recalled that in accordance with the Yalta 
accord the fleet should be divided in half. But, proceeding 
from the current realities, Ukraine will take only 15-20 percent 
of the ships. The remainder will go to pay off its debts to 
Russia. 
  Touching on the issue of a base for the Russian ships, the 
president said that he is insisting on their being stationed in 
Sevastopol. Balaklava could become the base for the Ukrainian 
Navy. Leonid Kravchuk will defend this proposal at his next 
meeting with Russia's President Boris Yeltsin. 
  However, as much as I might respect the defense ministers of 
the two states, the Black Sea Fleet issue should be resolved by 
the presidents and governments, Leonid Kravchuk emphasized. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

