<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Continuation of Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Continuation of Reportage on Black Sea Fleet Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kravchuk Rejects Third Party </H4>

<F P=102> LD2304165494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1614 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2304165494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The problem of the Black Sea Fleet should be solved 
at the negotiations between Ukraine and Russia without 
interference of "any third parties," Ukrainian President Leonid 
Kravchuk said in his interview with the World service Radio 
Ukrainy on Saturday. He emphasized that he had never spoken 
about participation of any other party in this process. 
  In Kravchuk's words, during his telephone talk with Viktor 
Chernomyrdin on Saturday he proposed to the Russian premier "to 
meet at the governmental level and to solve this problem with 
the help of experts and ministers." 
  "The statements voiced by ministers are not obligatory the 
truth in its final instance," Kravchuk said given various 
interpretations of the results of the negotiations in Sevastopol 
presented by Vitaliy Radetskyy and Pavel Grachev, heads of 
military departments of both countries. He expressed hope that 
the Black Sea Fleet problem would be solved "with Russia's 
president and government." 
  Kravchuk called the meeting between Ukrainian and Russian 
Defense Ministers held in Sevastopol on 21-22 April "a search 
for ways out" and called not to make any "far-reaching 
conclusions." 
  Kravchuk reassured that Ukraine "will support Russia's 
interest to have its base in Sevastopol" and noted that "nobody 
should be granted any unilateral advantages." 
  "One cannot force Russia to leave its bases in Crimea," said 
Kravchuk. He pointed out that "we must sign corresponding 
documents on rent of this bases by Russia for a definite time." 
"The main thing is to solve on which conditions and principles 
this would be done," Kravchuk said. 
  He underlined that he does not see any other way out -- 
"this 
problem cannot be solved by dictatorship or sanctions." 
  Kravchuk said that existence of foreign bases on the 
territory of any country not obligatory threatens to its 
sovereignty. As an example, he mentioned functioning of U.S. 
naval bases in several regions of the world. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

