<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk: Crimea's Call for Separation `Ill-Considered' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk: Crimea's Call for Separation `Ill-Considered' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2304195394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1758 
GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2304195394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by UKRINFORM correspondents Viktor Demidenko and </F>
Mikhail Melnik for TASS] 
  [Text] Kiev, 23 Apr -- I have said more than once, and will 
continue to insist in the future, that relations with Crimea, as 
a constituent part of Ukraine, should be built on a mutually 
advantageous basis. I believe that Yuriy Meshkov's statements 
regarding the separation of Crimea from Ukraine are 
ill-considered, Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk said in an 
exclusive interview with UKRINFORM correspondents today. 
  It would appear that Meshkov is doing this out of emotion or 
in order to aggravate the situation. His statements saying that 
Ukraine should give up Crimea are, to say the least, not 
serious. It is a territory of Ukraine that is recognized by the 
whole world community, Kravchuk said. 
  Kravchuk believes it is unlikely that the Republic of Crimea 
would be able to lead a proper life without Ukraine. If our 
links are severed, the peninsula's population of almost 3 
million will feel it straight away. But we do not want to give 
in to emotions and arrogance, the Ukrainian president stressed. 
  Kravchuk believes that Meshkov's illegal actions could 
become 
a barrier to friendly relations and partnership between Ukraine 
and Russia. That is a great responsibility for one man, who, 
profiting from current misfortunes and difficulties, flouting 
all international norms, is trying to separate Crimea from 
Ukraine. But apart from aggravating the situation, he will not 
succeed in doing anything, Kravchuk said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

