<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Cited on Composition of New Parliament </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Cited on Composition of New Parliament </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204190594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1709 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2204190594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk told journalists 
following the Supreme Soviet [as received] Friday session that 
338 deputies elected to new Ukrainian parliament were too few to 
make what he called cardinal decisions. 
  He expressed the hope that there would be a sufficient 
number 
of deputies to form a government, pass legislation and change 
the Constitution, for instance 430 or 440 deputies. 
  The run-off elections in 112 constituencies are scheduled 
for 
26 June. 
  Kravchuk did not say whether he would run for president. He 
only expressed his gratitude to those who want him to. The 
registration of presidential candidates will end on April 26. 
  He said that both the right and left-wing extremists in the 
new Supreme Soviet were ideologically Bolsheviks doing harm to 
Ukraine. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

