<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernobyl AES Official Underlines Safety Level </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernobyl AES Official Underlines Safety Level </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2204190894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1838 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2204190894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by UKRINFORM correspondent -- TASS] </F>
  [Text] Kiev 22 April TASS -- It is incorrect to estimate 
prospects of the Chernobyl nuclear power plant only negatively; 
calls to halt the plant are unjustified, Chernobyl nuclear power 
plant director Sergey Parashin told UKRINFORM on the eve of the 
8th anniversary of the Chernobyl accident. 
  In his words, the "situation around the Chernobyl power 
plant 
has been excessively politicized and some are trying to use it 
for pressure on Ukraine." 
  Speaking of the recent demands for immediate halt of the 
power plant, Parashin said specialists "have done much from 1986 
through now to increase the plant's safety and improve all the 
parameters of its operation. We have a clear plan of further 
measures to the effect and they are been consistently taken." 
  "Professionals are working at the Chernobyl nuclear power 
plant, and all the capacities are normally operated. I am 
confident that the current state of the plant is much better 
than that of many facilities of other branches," said the plant 
director. 
  The work of plant power units is under constant control over 
the state inspection for supervision over nuclear safety and 
other state bodies, he stressed. In case of any doubts, 
international experts, including those from the International 
Atomic Energy Agency, are invited. The situation at the 
"shelter" facility (the sarcophagus above the fourth power unit) 
is also under reliable control, and it provokes no serious 
concern over safety. 
  The plant director referred to the conclusions of the IAEA 
commission outlined in the commission's draft report on results 
of its work at the plant in March 1994: "The Chernobyl nuclear 
power plant has held all the arrangements scheduled for power 
units with RBMK reactors after the Chernobyl accident. The 
safety level at the first and third power units is equal to that 
of corresponding power units at the Leningrad, Kursk and 
Smolensk nuclear power plants. 
  "Despite the fact many highly-professional plant staffers 
have quitted, there are adequate resources for full staffing of 
the plant's six shifts to operate two power units. General 
impression of the control board personnel is `professionalism'." 
  Unfortunately, said the director, "these essential 
provisions 
of the report were not included in the IAEA press release 
circulated so widely in mass media bodies." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

