<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev: Partnership Program `Overpublicized' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grachev: Partnership Program `Overpublicized' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2504114794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1105 
GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2504114794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Shevtsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 25 Apr (ITAR-TASS) -- "In the first place, 
partnership means not deceiving one another and not letting one 
another down, taking account of partners' interests and not only 
one's own, not trying to place oneself above others, and all 
interested parties participating in a process of true 
partnership on an equal basis. And those are the principles of 
the Partnership for Peace program," Russian Defense Minister 
Pavel Grachev said at a news conference today. 
  The Russian defense minister believes that NATO's 
Partnership 
for Peace program has been over-publicized, although even the 
masters of the program have not yet put forward its specific 
principles and measures. Meanwhile, hundreds of scientific 
works have already been written on this topic, thousands of 
symposiums held, and millions spent on various visits, Pavel 
Grachev noted. 

</TEXT>

