<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev Urges End to Threat of Bosnia Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Grachev Urges End to Threat of Bosnia Air Strikes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2504125394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1230 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2504125394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Mikhail Shevtsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow April 25 TASS -- Russian Defence Minister 
Pavel Grachev called to drop the threat of NATO air strikes on 
Bosnia, especially of the massive ones which can make "the 
conflict uncontrollable and result in its spreading outside 
Bosnia-Herzegovina". 
  "In the military sphere NATO air strikes did not bring any 
results and will not bring them at present", he told a press 
conference on Monday. 
  The minister believes the major way to settle the conflict 
is 
to hold in the near future a meeting of the leaders of Russia, 
the United States, EU countries and the UN. The summit, 
according to Grachev, can be held in any European state and 
should involve also the political leadership of the whole of the 
former Yugoslavia. 
  Grachev urged to strengthen the peace-keeping forces in 
Gorazde and to avert bloodshed in the city itself. He informed 
that a 19-men strong Russian platoon will be transferred to 
Gorazde. The minister said it is also necessary to promote 
normal humanitarian provision for the population there. 
  Grachev is categorically against the withdrawal of Russian 
peace-keepers from Bosnia. "This would be an untimely and 
inappropriate decision fraught with a further political 
isolation of Russia in the world community. It is possible to 
pull out Russian forces from the region only after the 
settlement is reached by political means", he said. 
  The Russian minister believes it is not only Serbs who are 
to 
blame for the current crisis in Bosnia. Both conflicting sides 
are to blame, according to him. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

