<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Council Official Views Bosnian Solution </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Security Council Official Views Bosnian Solution </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2304140094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0639 
GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2304140094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Ivanova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 23 Apr -- Reserves for extinguishing the 
Bosnian conflict by peaceful means have not yet been exhausted 
and Boris Yeltsin's initiative is more likely than bombing and 
shelling to lead to an end to the war. This opinion was 
expressed by Oleg Lobov, secretary of the Security Council, in 
an interview with an ITAR-TASS correspondent. He reported that 
the Bosnian question was discussed at a meeting of the Security 
Council which had heard a report from Russian Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev as well as detailed information about the Russian 
president's initiative. 
  Oleg Lobov considers that a top-level meeting of the leaders 
of the world's leading countries and UN and CSCE 
representatives, with the participation of the warring sides, 
could yield the most positive results. 
  The Security Council secretary said that at the present time 
drafting work is being actively carried out on the concept of 
economic security. It is planned to examine the concept at a 
meeting of the council in November. Alongside military and 
social security, economic security is one of the most important 
areas of the council's activities. 
  The aim of the economic security program, Oleg Lobov said, 
is 
to stabilize the situation in the economy and to seek ways out 
of the crisis. Meanwhile, even before the program is adopted, a 
number of questions are being urgently tackled. These are 
questions connected with privatization, providing the Russian 
populace with medicines, the ecological problem, and land 
fertility. In the opinion of the Security Council secretary 
these could be described as global problems. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

